WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.247 --> 00:00:02.830
(bright music)

2
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:10.140
<v Host>Dr. Firnhaber is returning</v>

3
00:00:10.140 --> 00:00:13.620
and he is going to be leading our discussion

4
00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:14.940
on heart failure.

5
00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:16.080
Good morning, Jonathan.

6
00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:16.913
Thank you sir.

7
00:00:16.913 --> 00:00:17.746
And take it away.

8
00:00:17.746 --> 00:00:18.600
<v ->Good morning.</v>

9
00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:20.040
We are talking heart failure this morning.

10
00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:21.240
I still have nothing to disclose.

11
00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:22.690
Here are learning objectives.

12
00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.190
First things first, the heart failure guidelines

13
00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:28.320
were just updated.

14
00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.110
It seems like it was just, but it was still the end of 2022.

15
00:00:31.110 --> 00:00:33.060
So a little over a year now.

16
00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:34.890
Some stuff changed, some stuff didn't change.

17
00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:37.200
I'll show you what the differences are.

18
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:38.160
This did not change.

19
00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:40.350
So heart failure with reduced ejection fraction

20
00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:43.290
has an EF of 40% or less,

21
00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:45.090
sometimes called systolic heart failure.

22
00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:48.570
And when we're thinking about how to treat heart failure,

23
00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:50.970
this is what we know really well.

24
00:00:50.970 --> 00:00:53.340
If you're comparing heart failure with preserved

25
00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:56.670
versus heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.

26
00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:57.810
Reduced ejection fraction,

27
00:00:57.810 --> 00:00:59.640
very homogeneous group of people.

28
00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:01.560
When you've got a a cluster of patients

29
00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:03.210
that all behave the same,

30
00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:05.280
their hearts have the same physiology,

31
00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.470
there's a whole lot of similarities.

32
00:01:07.470 --> 00:01:08.790
There are a lot of good RCTs,

33
00:01:08.790 --> 00:01:09.990
a lot of randomized controlled trials

34
00:01:09.990 --> 00:01:12.390
that tell us exactly how to manage this.

35
00:01:12.390 --> 00:01:13.350
You'll see when we talk about

36
00:01:13.350 --> 00:01:15.840
heart failure preserved ejection fraction,

37
00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:17.160
totally heterogeneous group,

38
00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:21.930
meaning the ability to say, here's what always works

39
00:01:21.930 --> 00:01:23.280
is completely out the window.

40
00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:25.200
There's a lot of, well you can try this,

41
00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:28.590
usually do this, typically this, often this.

42
00:01:28.590 --> 00:01:30.630
But there's not the same body of evidence

43
00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:32.970
because this group is so heterogeneous

44
00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:34.680
or so homogeneous rather,

45
00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.560
this is a much easier group in many ways to say,

46
00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:39.363
here's what we do to manage this.

47
00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:43.200
So preserved ejection fraction is challenging

48
00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:44.430
'cause there's a lot of reasons

49
00:01:44.430 --> 00:01:47.640
that you can see people with heart failure symptoms,

50
00:01:47.640 --> 00:01:49.800
heart failure pathophysiology,

51
00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:52.170
but still a decent ejection fraction.

52
00:01:52.170 --> 00:01:54.090
And one of the things that I'd suggest

53
00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:56.760
as you're trying to wrap your head around heart failure

54
00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:58.680
is think of it more as a syndrome.

55
00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:01.530
Basically a syndrome of inadequate cardiac output

56
00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:03.030
to meet metabolic needs.

57
00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:05.850
And as you'll see when we talk, you can't,

58
00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:08.430
and you probably know, you can't look at someone and say,

59
00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:10.290
I can predict what your ejection fraction is,

60
00:02:10.290 --> 00:02:12.180
you are at 34%.

61
00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:15.090
We see people who come in massively fluid overloaded,

62
00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:18.660
barely able to walk, have class three, class four symptoms

63
00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:20.640
and they've got an EF of 55%.

64
00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:24.090
And then you see people who are moving along pretty good,

65
00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:25.560
got some class two symptoms,

66
00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:29.130
they're managing well and they've got an EF of 18%.

67
00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:31.380
So you can't glance at someone and say,

68
00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:33.150
I can predict your ejection fraction.

69
00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:35.760
So if you think you can let me know how you do it

70
00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.263
because I'm not sure.

71
00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:41.160
So what did change is they got rid

72
00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:45.030
of the 41 to 49% has been there.

73
00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:47.820
It was previously called borderline ejection fraction

74
00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:50.790
or borderline reduced, which is is a terrible term.

75
00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:52.920
I always think it's like being borderline pregnant.

76
00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:54.870
I mean it's just such a bad way

77
00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:56.610
of describing things in medicine.

78
00:02:56.610 --> 00:03:01.050
So it's now mildly reduced as the 40s, 41 to 49%.

79
00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:02.910
And then finally we've still got a category

80
00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:06.150
which is improved, meaning they used to be lower,

81
00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:08.790
they used to be in the reduced ejection fraction category,

82
00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:09.840
but we did a good job.

83
00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:13.080
We revascularized, we used a lot of good medications.

84
00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.140
Now we've got their EF above 40%.

85
00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:18.090
So they were bad but they're better,

86
00:03:18.090 --> 00:03:20.103
so we have an improved category.

87
00:03:22.050 --> 00:03:23.850
This is new-ish.

88
00:03:23.850 --> 00:03:25.950
And I don't know if y'all have seen,

89
00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:29.010
if your cardiologist that you work with use this much,

90
00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:30.510
at least in our academic medical center

91
00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:33.000
it still hasn't gained a whole lot of traction.

92
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.580
But there are now stages of heart failure.

93
00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:38.220
The reason that I think it's kind of

94
00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:40.440
not all that helpful personally is that,

95
00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:41.610
it's a really coarse cut.

96
00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:45.960
So stage A is at risk, meaning if you have hypertension

97
00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:49.110
or family history of heart failure, you're at risk.

98
00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.180
Labeling someone who doesn't have heart failure

99
00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:54.750
but has hypertension as stage A heart failure

100
00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:58.410
seems kind of odd but that's what they've done.

101
00:03:58.410 --> 00:03:59.820
Stage B is pre-heart failure,

102
00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:01.800
meaning you've got some structural damage,

103
00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:04.110
evidence of LVH for example

104
00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:06.480
that could eventually lead to heart failure

105
00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:08.160
but you don't really have heart failure yet,

106
00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:09.720
it's just pre-heart failure.

107
00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:10.890
That's stage B.

108
00:04:10.890 --> 00:04:14.190
Stage C then is everybody who is symptomatic,

109
00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:17.190
a huge swath of the heart failure population.

110
00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:20.790
And then you know, you move prayer abruptly to stage D,

111
00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:24.390
which is advanced, where people are almost in the end stage.

112
00:04:24.390 --> 00:04:27.090
So you're kind of, you know, at risk.

113
00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:29.400
You may be having, you're getting closer to heart failure,

114
00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:31.650
now you have heart failure, now you're advanced.

115
00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:35.013
So it's sort of course cuts but there they are.

116
00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.180
So first looking at medical therapy

117
00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:41.730
or GDMT guideline-directed medical therapy

118
00:04:41.730 --> 00:04:43.560
for reduced ejection fraction.

119
00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:47.310
Here's the big thing that changed in 2022

120
00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:50.070
is the addition of SGLT2 inhibitors

121
00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:51.930
in both the reduced and preserved

122
00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:54.750
ejection fraction GDMT categories.

123
00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:58.050
Interestingly enough, this is actually gets the same

124
00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:02.730
class of recommendation one for SGLT2 inhibitors.

125
00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:05.070
To me this was like the most landmark thing.

126
00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:06.360
Here is a class of drugs

127
00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:08.910
that is relatively new on the horizon.

128
00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:10.830
Relatively new in our armamentarium.

129
00:05:10.830 --> 00:05:12.390
It's not a drug that we actually

130
00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:14.670
had ever thought of as a heart failure drug.

131
00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:16.890
And the first time it hits the heart failure guidelines,

132
00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:19.290
it comes in as a class one recommendation.

133
00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:21.450
You know in there with heavy hitters like ARNI

134
00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:24.780
or brand name Entresto, beta-blockers, MRAs

135
00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:27.870
and ACE inhibitors or ARBs.

136
00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:30.303
So a huge, huge change.

137
00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:34.860
For mildly reduced ejection fraction

138
00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:36.420
preserved ejection fraction.

139
00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:38.310
You'll notice that the recommendations,

140
00:05:38.310 --> 00:05:39.230
the strength of recommendations

141
00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:41.490
in the AHA guidelines are lower.

142
00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:43.890
And the class of recommendations if you recall,

143
00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:46.650
class one is the stuff that we should do.

144
00:05:46.650 --> 00:05:48.840
Class one is the most evidence-based.

145
00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:51.270
It's the ones you have to have.

146
00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:53.910
If you go down to class three, class three is the don't.

147
00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:55.920
And I always pay good attention

148
00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:57.570
to class one recommendations.

149
00:05:57.570 --> 00:05:59.370
So what I know I have to do,

150
00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:01.620
pay equal attention to the class three recommendations.

151
00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.510
What's the stuff that I may have done in the past

152
00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.850
that is now considered bad?

153
00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.280
Class two recommendations are broken down to 2a,

154
00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:10.080
which are almost like class one,

155
00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:12.060
just the evidence isn't quite as strong.

156
00:06:12.060 --> 00:06:15.000
Class 2b, even weaker recommendations

157
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.890
but probably still okay.

158
00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:19.200
And you'll notice that with heart failure with reduced

159
00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:21.600
or with preserved ejection fraction,

160
00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:24.000
all the drugs that we're used to using

161
00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.190
ACE inhibitors, ARBs, beta blockers, MRAs,

162
00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.590
get a 2b recommendation.

163
00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:31.950
SGLT2 inhibitors get a 2a recommendation.

164
00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:35.160
So not only did this class of drugs hit the guidelines

165
00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:37.860
from a preserved ejection fraction standpoint

166
00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:38.940
actually hit the guidelines

167
00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.220
at a higher level of recommendation

168
00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:43.870
than the classic drugs that we use for heart failure.

169
00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:47.160
If you're familiar with the class one,

170
00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:51.120
class two, class three NYHA heart failure classifications,

171
00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:53.490
class one is no limitation.

172
00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:56.790
I will usually ask people, what makes you short of breath?

173
00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:59.400
Class two recommended, or class two heart failure.

174
00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:01.650
Are you short of breath with more strenuous activity?

175
00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:04.080
For example, carrying a couple of bags of groceries

176
00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:06.390
up some stairs from the car into the house.

177
00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.040
That'd be class two symptoms.

178
00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:08.873
Class three.

179
00:07:08.873 --> 00:07:10.950
Are you short of breath walking around the house?

180
00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:13.830
Class four, are you short of breath at rest?

181
00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:16.290
So there's the NYHA classification.

182
00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:18.360
So let's move on to a question.

183
00:07:18.360 --> 00:07:19.860
So we've got an 86-year-old woman

184
00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:21.210
who presents with shortness of breath

185
00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:22.590
and a non-productive cough.

186
00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:24.570
Think for just a minute 'cause we're gonna have like

187
00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:27.180
a differential diagnosis of two things.

188
00:07:27.180 --> 00:07:28.920
She's slightly tachypneic and tachycardic,

189
00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:30.660
temperature and BP are normal.

190
00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:32.220
Cardiac exam is normal but she's got

191
00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:34.320
bilateral crackles on lung exam

192
00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:37.263
and bilateral fluffy infiltrates noted on chest x-ray.

193
00:07:38.845 --> 00:07:40.950
CBC, metabolic panel, and initial troponin or normal.

194
00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:42.870
EKG shows sinus tachycardia.

195
00:07:42.870 --> 00:07:45.960
So the question is basically you're trying to decide

196
00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:49.350
this is a clinical picture that may be pneumonia,

197
00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:50.820
may be heart failure.

198
00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:53.160
Which labs might you use to help differentiate

199
00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:54.213
between the two?

200
00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:58.410
So we've got a d-dimer.

201
00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:00.750
I'm not gonna knock the ED folks.

202
00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:02.190
Emergency medicine and d-dimer

203
00:08:02.190 --> 00:08:04.803
just go together like macaroni and cheese.

204
00:08:04.803 --> 00:08:05.636
(audience laughing)

205
00:08:05.636 --> 00:08:07.230
BNP and procal.

206
00:08:07.230 --> 00:08:09.360
Serial troponin and CK.

207
00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:12.273
Sed rate and CRP or a lactic acid.

208
00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:19.710
Alright, excellent.

209
00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:21.663
Most went with BNP and procal.

210
00:08:22.530 --> 00:08:26.250
So really you're again trying to differentiate between,

211
00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:28.830
is this a pneumonia or is this heart failure?

212
00:08:28.830 --> 00:08:30.390
We need some additional data.

213
00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:33.570
BNP is a really helpful bit of information here.

214
00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:35.850
And oddly enough the B is for brain.

215
00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:37.320
'Cause when it was first characterized,

216
00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:38.310
apparently there's some of it

217
00:08:38.310 --> 00:08:40.620
that's found in the brain as well,

218
00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:42.480
but it doesn't come from the brain,

219
00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:44.910
it comes from the heart, from the ventricles actually.

220
00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:47.490
So brain natriuretic peptide.

221
00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:50.430
Natriuretic meaning sodium out in the urine,

222
00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:54.810
sodium in the urine, is the intent of BNP.

223
00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:58.830
It is released in direct proportion to ventricular stretch.

224
00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:01.260
Meaning, if you're thinking about BNP elevations

225
00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:03.600
in heart failure with reduced

226
00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:05.970
versus preserved ejection fraction,

227
00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:07.530
those with preserved ejection fraction

228
00:09:07.530 --> 00:09:10.620
typically have thicker less compliant ventricles.

229
00:09:10.620 --> 00:09:13.440
There's less end diastolic stretch.

230
00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:15.420
Therefore lower levels of BNP

231
00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:17.400
with preserved ejection fraction.

232
00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:19.230
Those who have reduced ejection fraction,

233
00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:21.450
typically their ventricles are kind of big baggy

234
00:09:21.450 --> 00:09:24.480
and have this huge end diastolic volume.

235
00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:26.700
Typically you see much higher BNP elevations

236
00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:28.833
with reduced ejection fraction.

237
00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:31.320
Also make sure you recognize

238
00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:33.030
that it is partially renally cleared.

239
00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:34.890
So for some patients who have

240
00:09:34.890 --> 00:09:36.750
more significant levels of CKD,

241
00:09:36.750 --> 00:09:40.020
you may need to establish a BNP baseline that says,

242
00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:43.620
when they are stable, you know dry or euvolemic

243
00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:45.450
and then you check a BNP to say,

244
00:09:45.450 --> 00:09:47.970
here's where they are at their finest

245
00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:50.280
and it may not be a normal BNP,

246
00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:52.740
especially if they you know have poor renal function.

247
00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:55.260
The BNP, they're secreting that you're measuring today,

248
00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:56.730
they may have secreted two weeks ago

249
00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:58.330
and it's still lingering around.

250
00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:01.680
Numberwise, BNP less than a hundred

251
00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:04.380
is typically a cut point to say

252
00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:06.690
this is unlikely due to ventricular stretch,

253
00:10:06.690 --> 00:10:08.400
unlikely due to heart failure.

254
00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:11.100
Above 400 is usually the point where we say okay,

255
00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:13.290
this is pretty likely heart failure.

256
00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:15.900
Obviously there's a gray zone in there, 100 to 400,

257
00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:19.170
lots of things can cause that degree of BNP elevation.

258
00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:22.230
Things that cause increased right-sided pressures.

259
00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.090
So like pulmonary embolism

260
00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:27.270
with especially with a high clot burden,

261
00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:30.453
cor pulmonale can cause BNP elevation as well.

262
00:10:31.350 --> 00:10:34.200
One little caveat here is right here at the bottom

263
00:10:34.200 --> 00:10:36.750
and that is that that patients who are more obese

264
00:10:36.750 --> 00:10:39.090
tend to secrete less BNP

265
00:10:39.090 --> 00:10:42.000
and the lower, the levels are basically lower.

266
00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.970
So if you're saying 100 is my usual cut point

267
00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:47.010
to start getting excited,

268
00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:50.610
drop that down to close to 50 for someone who's more obese,

269
00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:52.980
they tend to secrete less BNP,

270
00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:54.630
their levels are typically lower.

271
00:10:57.150 --> 00:10:58.140
Just a quick point here,

272
00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:01.020
there is at least in the older 2017 guidelines,

273
00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:04.440
there was some suggestion that using BNP earlier

274
00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.240
in the evaluation of patients

275
00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:08.700
who are either maybe in the at risk

276
00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:12.390
or pre-heart failure categories may be useful

277
00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:14.160
if you take that information

278
00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:15.840
and combine it always with this, you know,

279
00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:17.400
incredibly comprehensive program

280
00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:19.860
that none of us have availability of

281
00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:24.153
but that may decreased risk of progression of heart failure.

282
00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:28.290
Good things on echos.

283
00:11:28.290 --> 00:11:29.880
It just makes me cringe

284
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.530
when our residents get an echo report back

285
00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:34.560
and like scroll right to the bottom as like I want the EF.

286
00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.060
But you went past all the good stuff,

287
00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:37.260
there's a lot of good information there

288
00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:38.250
that you just went past.

289
00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:40.800
I mean EF is important obviously we wanna know that.

290
00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:42.270
But a lot of other good things

291
00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.430
that you can pick up from the echo.

292
00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:49.110
Really an objective or an assessment of LV function.

293
00:11:49.110 --> 00:11:51.660
Is there evidence of wall motion abnormalities?

294
00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:53.670
What's the LV thickness looks like?

295
00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:56.100
How contractile is the left ventricle?

296
00:11:56.100 --> 00:11:58.920
What does the relaxation phase look like?

297
00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:01.470
Obviously you're looking for valvular abnormalities

298
00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:04.140
and impairment of diastolic function.

299
00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:06.150
And there are different ways that that can be described,

300
00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:08.100
it's now more consistently,

301
00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:11.370
at least our cardiologists will more consistently describe.

302
00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:12.203
There's a sentence,

303
00:12:12.203 --> 00:12:14.450
here's what the diastolic function looks like.

304
00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:17.610
So systolic dysfunction doesn't necessarily

305
00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:19.860
have to have a big baggy ventricle.

306
00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:22.410
You may have a normal size ventricle

307
00:12:22.410 --> 00:12:25.470
that is just impaired by a lot of ischemic heart disease,

308
00:12:25.470 --> 00:12:28.410
multiple areas of wall motion abnormality or akinesis,

309
00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:31.200
meaning the ventricle doesn't contract at all

310
00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:33.720
even though the ventricle size looks okay.

311
00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:35.580
More often than not in patients who have

312
00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:38.340
impaired diastolic function tend to have thicker ventricles

313
00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:40.263
that just don't relax well.

314
00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:44.370
So the physiologic basis of treatment.

315
00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:45.570
Here are the drugs that we use

316
00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:48.720
for heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.

317
00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:52.140
And you'll notice that in essence we're undoing

318
00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:54.510
all of these physiologic things.

319
00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:58.230
So you say when heart, when cardiac output is poor,

320
00:12:58.230 --> 00:12:59.670
remember cardiac output is a function

321
00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:03.360
of stroke volume plus heart rate, cardiac output is poor.

322
00:13:03.360 --> 00:13:05.100
And if we think of heart failure as a syndrome

323
00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:08.880
of inadequate cardiac output to meet metabolic needs,

324
00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:10.860
poor cardiac output leads to

325
00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:13.680
a whole bunch of compensatory mechanisms.

326
00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:16.170
You have increased sympathetic outflow,

327
00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:18.600
increase contractility, increase heart rate

328
00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:20.520
to improve cardiac output.

329
00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:21.690
You want to retain sodium,

330
00:13:21.690 --> 00:13:25.620
therefore retain fluid, want to vasoconstrict.

331
00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:29.220
And all these things make perfect sense if you were to say,

332
00:13:29.220 --> 00:13:30.900
perhaps the reason for cardiac output

333
00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:33.030
if we go back to caveman times would be,

334
00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:35.310
you just got gored by a saber-toothed tiger

335
00:13:35.310 --> 00:13:37.860
and lost 50% of your blood volume

336
00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:40.230
as a reason for poor cardiac output,

337
00:13:40.230 --> 00:13:44.460
all these mechanisms make perfect sense in that case, right?

338
00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:48.930
But we don't get gored by saber-toothed tigers often today

339
00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:51.750
and we still have poor cardiac output

340
00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:54.450
but the compensatory mechanisms have not changed.

341
00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:57.720
So the mechanisms that are useful in acute blood loss

342
00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:01.110
become counterproductive in reduced ejection fraction

343
00:14:01.110 --> 00:14:03.480
that's due to ischemic heart disease for example.

344
00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:07.950
So we're trying to counteract the compensatory mechanisms.

345
00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:10.080
Long-term sympathetic outflow

346
00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:12.330
causes cardiac muscle apoptosis

347
00:14:12.330 --> 00:14:14.970
or cardiac cell muscle death.

348
00:14:14.970 --> 00:14:16.380
Long-term retention of fluid

349
00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:18.630
or recognized ends up having people congested,

350
00:14:18.630 --> 00:14:20.970
long-term sodium retention, blood pressure goes up,

351
00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:21.870
they get more congested,

352
00:14:21.870 --> 00:14:23.970
they get more ischemic, et cetera, et cetera.

353
00:14:23.970 --> 00:14:28.260
So all of our attempts here are to in essence sabotage

354
00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:30.660
or take away the compensatory mechanisms.

355
00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:33.210
So we do preload reduction,

356
00:14:33.210 --> 00:14:34.087
diuretics and nitrates help there.

357
00:14:34.087 --> 00:14:36.270
Afterload reduction, ACE inhibitors,

358
00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:38.010
ARBs are the prototypes.

359
00:14:38.010 --> 00:14:39.480
Sympathetic blockade obviously,

360
00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:40.740
and don't forget that it is the

361
00:14:40.740 --> 00:14:43.350
renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.

362
00:14:43.350 --> 00:14:47.550
We always have to focus on aldosterone antagonism.

363
00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:48.810
So let's move on to another question.

364
00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:50.670
We've got a 72-year-old male

365
00:14:50.670 --> 00:14:53.550
with a new diagnosis of hypertensive cardiomyopathy.

366
00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:57.720
His EF is 30%, he has dyspnea at rest,

367
00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:01.110
class four symptoms and with minimal exertion.

368
00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:02.700
Okay that's class three.

369
00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:03.810
Which one of the following drugs

370
00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:06.123
will reduce his mortality risk?

371
00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:08.940
All sorts of choices.

372
00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:13.940
Atenolol, lisinopril, digoxin, furosemide and nifedipine.

373
00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.840
All right, so lisinopril.

374
00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:23.970
Realistically, if I put any ACE inhibitor

375
00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:27.360
or any ARB up here, it would've been a correct answer.

376
00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:30.090
As a matter of fact, if you're in an exam situation

377
00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:31.920
and the question is asking about

378
00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:34.500
some positive thing that is you want to do

379
00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:37.620
and ACE inhibitors on the list, probably choose that

380
00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:40.800
'cause it's almost always good for whatever ails you.

381
00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:45.480
So ACE inhibitors and a close, close second is ARBs

382
00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:48.480
both reduce morbidity and mortality.

383
00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:49.313
Really importantly,

384
00:15:49.313 --> 00:15:51.600
there is not a threshold ejection fraction

385
00:15:51.600 --> 00:15:53.910
where you say this patient will no longer benefit

386
00:15:53.910 --> 00:15:55.890
from an ACE inhibitor or ARB.

387
00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:57.900
You may not start with massive doses,

388
00:15:57.900 --> 00:16:00.090
but there's still no threshold ejection fraction

389
00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:02.820
where you say no longer a consideration.

390
00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:03.900
We talked about angioedema

391
00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:05.850
and we were talking about heart failure.

392
00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:07.500
Obviously if blood pressure's low,

393
00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:10.200
be cautious and start slowly.

394
00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:13.233
Decreased renal function, hyperkalemia, all possibilities.

395
00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:17.520
Here's a list of some ACE inhibitors in heart failure.

396
00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:19.590
Also recognize that when you're treating,

397
00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:21.390
if you happen to for whatever reason,

398
00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:23.550
still be using Captopril, Enalapril,

399
00:16:23.550 --> 00:16:25.440
it is dosed differently for heart failure

400
00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:27.210
than for blood pressure for hypertension.

401
00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:30.240
Captopril, from a antihypertensive standpoint,

402
00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:31.830
you can dose twice daily.

403
00:16:31.830 --> 00:16:34.860
From a heart failure perspective, it's thrice daily.

404
00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:37.800
Enalapril, I'm still not certain why anyone uses Enalapril

405
00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:40.080
once daily for heart for hypertension,

406
00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:43.620
but it is a b.i.d. drug from a heart failure perspective

407
00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:45.813
and some ARBs as well.

408
00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:51.810
Beta blockers, if you ask one of our cardiologists

409
00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:52.800
got someone with heart failure

410
00:16:52.800 --> 00:16:54.510
with reduced ejection fraction,

411
00:16:54.510 --> 00:16:55.860
which do we want to start first?

412
00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:58.440
ACE inhibitor slash ARB or beta blocker?

413
00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:00.150
The answer is yes.

414
00:17:00.150 --> 00:17:02.160
And the answer might change,

415
00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:04.560
you know if Jupiter's in you know, alignment with Mars

416
00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:05.400
or something like that.

417
00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:08.043
But it is basically they are all important.

418
00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:12.780
Beta blockers, even with below very low ejection fractions

419
00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:14.700
still have benefit.

420
00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:17.340
There's no absolute threshold ejection fraction.

421
00:17:17.340 --> 00:17:20.100
The last sentence there's really critical though.

422
00:17:20.100 --> 00:17:22.200
Beta blockers are started when the patient is

423
00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:25.110
hemodynamically stable and euvolemic.

424
00:17:25.110 --> 00:17:26.640
If you remember from the Q and A yesterday,

425
00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:28.170
someone asked about,

426
00:17:28.170 --> 00:17:32.550
in essence reflexively starting a rate limiting drug

427
00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:34.170
for someone who is tachycardic.

428
00:17:34.170 --> 00:17:35.520
You said no, you gotta first figure out

429
00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.680
why the tachycardia is there.

430
00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:39.240
Recall in heart failure,

431
00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:42.570
the tachycardia might simply be the heart's mechanism

432
00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:44.430
to improve cardiac output.

433
00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:47.583
If stroke volume is really tiny, stroke volume plus heart,

434
00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:52.110
stroke volume plus heart rate equals cardiac output.

435
00:17:52.110 --> 00:17:54.420
Tiny stroke volume, heart rate may be the only thing

436
00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:56.340
that's maintaining cardiac output.

437
00:17:56.340 --> 00:17:58.890
So hemodynamically stable and euvolemic

438
00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:00.993
are the times to start beta blockers.

439
00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:04.860
Remember there are only three beta blockers

440
00:18:04.860 --> 00:18:07.200
that have data for heart failure,

441
00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:10.050
metoprolol succinate is the long acting version.

442
00:18:10.050 --> 00:18:11.010
You're probably familiar,

443
00:18:11.010 --> 00:18:12.750
one of the cool things about this tablet

444
00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:15.090
is one of the very, very few long acting

445
00:18:15.090 --> 00:18:16.440
or extended release tablets

446
00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:18.840
that is actually designed to be cut.

447
00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:20.730
So there's no coding on it that says

448
00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:22.680
this is what makes it long acting.

449
00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:25.230
It's not like a delivery mechanism for a pill,

450
00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:26.640
for medicine or something.

451
00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:28.860
It is a bunch of little beads that are compressed together.

452
00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:32.250
So it's scored designed to be cut, cut away.

453
00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:35.220
Metoprolol can be started at teeny little doses.

454
00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:38.430
Same with carvedilol, which is an alpha beta blocker.

455
00:18:38.430 --> 00:18:40.830
Bisoprolol is the one that is often forgotten

456
00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:43.380
but is a really cool beta blocker 'cause it's once a day.

457
00:18:43.380 --> 00:18:47.460
It's relatively inexpensive, easy to use,

458
00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:50.160
tend to use a fair amount of beta blocker,

459
00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:51.060
bisoprolol rather.

460
00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:55.230
The cautions are really straightforward.

461
00:18:55.230 --> 00:18:57.900
Hemodynamic instability of course, heart block,

462
00:18:57.900 --> 00:19:00.150
and it's not just a first degree AV block,

463
00:19:00.150 --> 00:19:02.640
it's like a second degree type two

464
00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:03.840
or a third degree AV block

465
00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:05.400
obviously fix that first

466
00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:08.340
before you do something with a beta blocker.

467
00:19:08.340 --> 00:19:10.200
Bradycardia is relative.

468
00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:12.690
If someone's got a resting heart rate of 58, fine,

469
00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:14.100
put them on a beta blocker.

470
00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:15.240
If their heart rate is 30,

471
00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:17.670
then figure out why it is that low.

472
00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:19.050
Alright, another question.

473
00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:22.200
We've got a 69-year-old woman with hypertension, previous MI

474
00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:24.930
and EF of 32% who's seen in your office.

475
00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:25.763
Comfortable at rest

476
00:19:25.763 --> 00:19:27.570
but is breathless when walking upstairs.

477
00:19:27.570 --> 00:19:31.170
So I put that as a class two symptomatology.

478
00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:33.493
Current meds, atorvastatin, lisinopril,

479
00:19:33.493 --> 00:19:35.910
metoprolol succinate, the long acting version,

480
00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:39.120
furosemide and aspirin, BP 132 over 78.

481
00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:40.560
Exam, her heart has no murmur,

482
00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:42.570
her lungs have some bibasilar crackles,

483
00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:44.190
a little bit of edema.

484
00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:47.790
EKG, heart rate's 52, she's got multifocal PVCs.

485
00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:49.533
Her QRS duration is 0.1.

486
00:19:52.050 --> 00:19:53.400
A lot of information.

487
00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:56.100
So the question is adding which one of the following

488
00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:58.740
would help to decrease both mortality

489
00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:01.440
and decrease the risk of hospitalization?

490
00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:04.090
So it's kind of a what was missing from this picture.

491
00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:09.483
We've got spironolactone, digoxin, furosemide and losartan.

492
00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:15.060
Awesome.

493
00:20:15.060 --> 00:20:18.180
and I hope that this was, you looked at this and said,

494
00:20:18.180 --> 00:20:19.530
gosh, you're missing an MRA,

495
00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:22.140
you're missing spironolactone in that picture.

496
00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:23.820
So we have spironolactone,

497
00:20:23.820 --> 00:20:25.620
which the prototype eplerenone known as

498
00:20:25.620 --> 00:20:29.070
basically spironolactone without the hormonal side effects.

499
00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:32.280
One of the questions came up in the Q and A yesterday,

500
00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:34.260
or at least on the written questions,

501
00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:37.320
why would you use spironolactone in the first base

502
00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:39.630
if it causes potentially hormonal side effects

503
00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:40.780
and eplerenone doesn't?

504
00:20:41.850 --> 00:20:45.240
Not at all expensive, very expensive.

505
00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:46.920
There's a good place to start.

506
00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:48.840
And not everybody gets hormonal side effects

507
00:20:48.840 --> 00:20:49.980
from spironolactone.

508
00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:51.180
But if that is an issue

509
00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:53.430
then eplerenone is an excellent option.

510
00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:57.960
I do recognize that in cases of worsening CKD,

511
00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:02.700
once you cross over from the CKD three to four threshold,

512
00:21:02.700 --> 00:21:05.640
then ideally you need to start looking at dialing back

513
00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:07.710
or getting rid of an MRA.

514
00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:09.540
They do cause potassium increase.

515
00:21:09.540 --> 00:21:13.110
So if potassium at baseline is higher than four and a half,

516
00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:14.913
be following that closely as well.

517
00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:16.980
NSAIDs and COX-2 inhibitors

518
00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:18.270
basically reduce renal function

519
00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:22.387
and worsen the hyperkalemia associated with an MRA.

520
00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:27.720
So those are the big GDMT

521
00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:30.060
guideline-directed medical therapy drugs.

522
00:21:30.060 --> 00:21:33.120
What if either someone can't tolerate them,

523
00:21:33.120 --> 00:21:35.670
you're not getting enough improvement in symptoms,

524
00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:39.300
what if those are not, you know the best options for you

525
00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:42.137
always fall back to the tried and true

526
00:21:42.137 --> 00:21:44.520
hydralazine isosorbide combination.

527
00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.500
There is brand name BiDil

528
00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:49.230
which like so many brand name drugs like that.

529
00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:52.380
Basically BiDil is a combination that you can't create

530
00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:56.580
with existing tablet sizes of hydralazine and isosorbide.

531
00:21:56.580 --> 00:21:59.610
Whether there's pixie dust that's in BiDil also

532
00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:02.220
that makes it work better than a combination

533
00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:05.010
of hydralazine and isosorbide you could make for yourself.

534
00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:08.370
I don't know, but BiDil is BiDil.

535
00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:10.050
Think of that actually the,

536
00:22:10.050 --> 00:22:12.690
there's actually one study that looked at

537
00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:14.160
class three, class four heart failure

538
00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:16.470
in African American patients as the niche

539
00:22:16.470 --> 00:22:19.830
where BiDil tends to truly shine.

540
00:22:19.830 --> 00:22:21.300
Reasonable in other individuals,

541
00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:23.370
but that is the kinda little carve out

542
00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:25.983
where the data was particularly strong.

543
00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:29.610
The dihydropyridine purine calcium channel blockers,

544
00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:31.934
which we talked about yesterday as being all the pines,

545
00:22:31.934 --> 00:22:35.460
amlodipine, nisoldipine, nicardipine, felodipine, et cetera.

546
00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:38.550
Think of these as antihypertensive drugs

547
00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:41.340
that you can use in heart failure.

548
00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:43.650
They're not drugs for heart failure.

549
00:22:43.650 --> 00:22:46.230
However, if you have exhausted all of the medications

550
00:22:46.230 --> 00:22:48.150
that you'd normally use for heart failure

551
00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:51.600
and you still need additional blood pressure reduction,

552
00:22:51.600 --> 00:22:53.100
that's where dihydropyridine calcium

553
00:22:53.100 --> 00:22:54.870
channel blocker can come in.

554
00:22:54.870 --> 00:22:56.130
From a heart failure standpoint,

555
00:22:56.130 --> 00:22:57.600
they're decidedly neutral.

556
00:22:57.600 --> 00:22:59.670
Don't make things worse, don't make things better,

557
00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.650
they simply lower blood pressure

558
00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:04.150
and they do so without affecting cardiac function.

559
00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:07.260
Alright, question four.

560
00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:10.350
We've got a 62-year-old man with hypertension,

561
00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:12.120
heart failure with reduced ejection fraction

562
00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:14.190
who reports dyspnea on exertion.

563
00:23:14.190 --> 00:23:15.980
Current meds, lisinopril, carvedilol,

564
00:23:15.980 --> 00:23:17.850
spironolactone, furosemide.

565
00:23:17.850 --> 00:23:21.540
On exam, he's at 128 over 82, pulse is 62.

566
00:23:21.540 --> 00:23:22.980
EF is 35%.

567
00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:25.773
BNP is a bit elevated at 250.

568
00:23:27.540 --> 00:23:28.560
There's all of that.

569
00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:31.530
So current AHA guidelines recommend which of the following

570
00:23:31.530 --> 00:23:35.700
to further reduce morbidity and mortality.

571
00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:38.790
Would you ramp up the furosemide?

572
00:23:38.790 --> 00:23:39.750
Add ivabradine?

573
00:23:39.750 --> 00:23:40.710
If you don't know what that is,

574
00:23:40.710 --> 00:23:42.900
I will tell you in just a moment.

575
00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:46.200
Add some losartan on top of I think the lisinopril.

576
00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:49.650
Stop enalapril and start sacubitril slash valsartan

577
00:23:49.650 --> 00:23:50.853
brand name Entresto.

578
00:23:56.580 --> 00:23:58.020
Alright, excellent.

579
00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:00.060
So most are going with ARNI,

580
00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:02.190
which is such a great acronym.

581
00:24:02.190 --> 00:24:05.793
I like that it's got a name like a real human sort of name.

582
00:24:07.170 --> 00:24:11.700
So neprilysin is basically another hormone

583
00:24:11.700 --> 00:24:15.360
that we ideally want to antagonize in heart failure.

584
00:24:15.360 --> 00:24:20.040
What neprilysin inhibition does causes some vasodilation

585
00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:21.540
also some natriuresis,

586
00:24:21.540 --> 00:24:23.193
sodium goes out in the urine.

587
00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:27.330
Combination is approved up to class three

588
00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:29.730
but not class four, heart failure.

589
00:24:29.730 --> 00:24:32.010
So if you have someone who is still symptomatic

590
00:24:32.010 --> 00:24:34.620
despite maximum GDMT

591
00:24:34.620 --> 00:24:38.430
and they're not at class four but up to class three,

592
00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:42.210
then switching over from either the ACE or ARB to ARNI

593
00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:45.333
and the only one that's there is Entresto is helpful.

594
00:24:46.290 --> 00:24:50.790
SGLT2 inhibitors and to be clear,

595
00:24:50.790 --> 00:24:52.200
the data here is still not,

596
00:24:52.200 --> 00:24:53.033
if you're looking for these,

597
00:24:53.033 --> 00:24:55.320
these massive absolute risk reductions

598
00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:58.080
in heart failure, hospitalizations and death and so on,

599
00:24:58.080 --> 00:25:01.080
it is in the single digit percentage range.

600
00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:03.930
So it's not a massive, massive improvement.

601
00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:06.570
But nonetheless the data is there.

602
00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:08.640
There is to date no head-to-head data

603
00:25:08.640 --> 00:25:10.320
among the SGLT2 inhibitors.

604
00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:12.510
So when you see some that,

605
00:25:12.510 --> 00:25:14.400
well this may be better, this one may be better here,

606
00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:15.810
this one may be better there.

607
00:25:15.810 --> 00:25:17.730
It's truly the best data that's out there.

608
00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:20.220
And as you probably recognize,

609
00:25:20.220 --> 00:25:23.460
each study will assign patients a little bit differently.

610
00:25:23.460 --> 00:25:25.230
Each study will carve its data up and say,

611
00:25:25.230 --> 00:25:27.480
well in this little subset here,

612
00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:29.010
this patient group with this

613
00:25:29.010 --> 00:25:32.190
and this and this characteristic, this drug did better.

614
00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:35.460
So there's always gonna be those kind of odd comparisons.

615
00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:37.950
And so if you're looking for what is the best

616
00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:41.760
SGLT2 inhibitor, the answer is not really known yet.

617
00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:42.960
But heart failure with

618
00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:45.510
reduced ejection fraction or preserved

619
00:25:45.510 --> 00:25:48.870
with or without diabetes up to class four heart failure

620
00:25:48.870 --> 00:25:53.073
and in conjunction with background of GDMT.

621
00:25:55.350 --> 00:25:56.183
There we go.

622
00:25:56.183 --> 00:25:59.400
Ivabradine which is brand name Corlanor

623
00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:01.620
is a sinus node modulator.

624
00:26:01.620 --> 00:26:02.970
The bottom line is that,

625
00:26:02.970 --> 00:26:06.420
if despite maximally tolerated beta blockade,

626
00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:08.550
someone still has elevated heart rate

627
00:26:08.550 --> 00:26:10.950
that's associated with worse outcomes.

628
00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:13.560
Ivabradine does nothing other than tell the sinus node

629
00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:14.970
to slow the heck down.

630
00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:15.803
That's it.

631
00:26:15.803 --> 00:26:17.820
It's a sinus node modulator.

632
00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:21.420
It is not one, I'll be honest, I've never prescribed myself.

633
00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:23.310
I've got probably two patients

634
00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:26.100
who see our cardiologist in our heart failure clinic

635
00:26:26.100 --> 00:26:28.980
and we've got a couple of patients who take this medication.

636
00:26:28.980 --> 00:26:30.870
But it is basically just be aware

637
00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:32.400
that it is a sinus node modulator.

638
00:26:32.400 --> 00:26:33.750
It slows down heart rate

639
00:26:33.750 --> 00:26:36.873
but does not do so in a beta blocker type of mechanism.

640
00:26:38.100 --> 00:26:39.150
Alrighty, next question.

641
00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:42.300
We've got a 70-year-old man with history of MI.

642
00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:45.120
Now has heart with EF of 30%.

643
00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:47.280
EKG shows sinus rhythm.

644
00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:49.590
Question is, which one of the following medications

645
00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:51.990
that he's currently taking is potentially harmful

646
00:26:51.990 --> 00:26:53.643
and should be discontinued?

647
00:26:54.810 --> 00:26:58.473
Which of these doesn't fit in a heart failure regimen?

648
00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:04.920
Awesome.

649
00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:06.570
Diltiazem.

650
00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:07.950
That is the one.

651
00:27:07.950 --> 00:27:09.210
And the numbers keep going up.

652
00:27:09.210 --> 00:27:10.860
So there are good and bad drugs for heart failure.

653
00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:12.720
We've talked a lot about the good drugs.

654
00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:15.090
There are some drugs that are not as good.

655
00:27:15.090 --> 00:27:17.280
Digoxin and furosemide are tough ones

656
00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:18.990
because there's not great data

657
00:27:18.990 --> 00:27:21.720
that they actually improve mortality.

658
00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:22.890
Some data that digoxin

659
00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:26.250
may reduce heart failure, hospitalizations.

660
00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:27.480
Loop diuretics.

661
00:27:27.480 --> 00:27:29.310
Can you imagine trying to do a study

662
00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:33.180
that is randomized, controlled, has a placebo arm

663
00:27:33.180 --> 00:27:35.340
that says we're going to evaluate

664
00:27:35.340 --> 00:27:37.410
whether loop diuretics improve

665
00:27:37.410 --> 00:27:40.140
or do not improve outcomes in heart failure.

666
00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:42.060
No one's gonna do the study and no one really cares

667
00:27:42.060 --> 00:27:43.650
because we're still gonna use loop diuretics

668
00:27:43.650 --> 00:27:46.380
to treat heart failure because they diurese well.

669
00:27:46.380 --> 00:27:48.360
So we don't really have good data there

670
00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:50.130
and there probably never will be,

671
00:27:50.130 --> 00:27:52.350
but we're still gonna use loop diuretics.

672
00:27:52.350 --> 00:27:54.030
I mentioned yesterday that the

673
00:27:54.030 --> 00:27:56.220
dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers

674
00:27:56.220 --> 00:27:59.040
are typically not considered negative inotropes,

675
00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:02.400
whereas the non dihydropyridines verapamil and diltiazem

676
00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:06.120
are negative inotropes, they decrease cardiac contractility.

677
00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:08.070
There are very few if any situations

678
00:28:08.070 --> 00:28:11.130
where these are useful from a heart failure perspective.

679
00:28:11.130 --> 00:28:12.993
You can use better drugs than these.

680
00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.640
There was an attempt, if we look at BNP and say,

681
00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:22.260
well BNP is released for a reason natriuretic peptide.

682
00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:24.750
Gosh, what if we were to make synthetic BNP?

683
00:28:24.750 --> 00:28:27.090
Wouldn't that be a handy thing for heart failure?

684
00:28:27.090 --> 00:28:30.510
It turns out it did actually cause vasodilation

685
00:28:30.510 --> 00:28:33.360
but it didn't really affect hospitalization or death

686
00:28:33.360 --> 00:28:36.573
and so that medication was basically abandoned.

687
00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:39.150
Most antiarrhythmic drugs are not good

688
00:28:39.150 --> 00:28:40.530
from a heart failure standpoint.

689
00:28:40.530 --> 00:28:43.620
I hope NSAIDs make you cringe when you think about them.

690
00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:45.030
Plus heart failure.

691
00:28:45.030 --> 00:28:47.040
DCTs, and I still leave it as plural

692
00:28:47.040 --> 00:28:48.870
even though I don't know if you could find

693
00:28:48.870 --> 00:28:51.840
a tablet of rosiglitazone in the US anymore,

694
00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:54.183
but pioglitazone as the prototype there.

695
00:28:55.140 --> 00:28:57.630
Contraindicated in class three, class four.

696
00:28:57.630 --> 00:28:59.550
In lower stages of heart failure

697
00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:01.290
you could still consider using the drug

698
00:29:01.290 --> 00:29:04.080
but recognize that it does cause fluid retention.

699
00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:07.350
Incidentally, that is not a dose dependent mechanism.

700
00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:10.170
It is, so if someone's on 45 of pioglitazone

701
00:29:10.170 --> 00:29:11.520
and you're like other retaining fluid,

702
00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:14.040
I'll drop down to 30 or 15.

703
00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:14.873
No go.

704
00:29:14.873 --> 00:29:16.110
The drug simply has to go.

705
00:29:16.110 --> 00:29:17.433
It is not dose dependent.

706
00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:20.370
Preserved ejection fraction.

707
00:29:20.370 --> 00:29:22.290
This is not just diastolic dysfunction,

708
00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:25.140
it is multifactorial, very heterogeneous.

709
00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:28.800
Most often is hypertensive LV hypertrophy.

710
00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.620
The things we see clinically, chronotropic incompetence,

711
00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:34.680
meaning someone starts to walk or starts to exercise,

712
00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:36.480
their heart rate doesn't pick up quickly.

713
00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:38.370
They get to the top of a flight of stairs

714
00:29:38.370 --> 00:29:40.740
and they have to stand there and wait for their heart rate

715
00:29:40.740 --> 00:29:44.130
and their cardiac output to catch up to what they just did.

716
00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:45.060
Once it does catch up,

717
00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:47.040
takes forever for them to slow back down.

718
00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:48.360
Put them on the treadmill,

719
00:29:48.360 --> 00:29:50.160
you're four minutes, five minutes into recovery,

720
00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:50.993
they're still sitting there

721
00:29:50.993 --> 00:29:52.983
clipping along on 130 beats a minute.

722
00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:58.260
Evidence-based treatment recommendations are limited.

723
00:29:58.260 --> 00:29:59.930
It's an incredibly heterogeneous group.

724
00:29:59.930 --> 00:30:02.010
It is hard to make broad recommendations

725
00:30:02.010 --> 00:30:03.540
on what always works.

726
00:30:03.540 --> 00:30:05.940
We do recognize that treating hypertension

727
00:30:05.940 --> 00:30:07.830
is the top of the list.

728
00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:11.040
Increased risk of atrial fibrillation is associated.

729
00:30:11.040 --> 00:30:13.413
Diabetes, CKD also associated.

730
00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:18.870
The treatment always has the word careful in front of it.

731
00:30:18.870 --> 00:30:22.380
Careful preload reduction, careful heart rate reduction.

732
00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:23.670
These folks tend to be,

733
00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:26.730
in some cases sometimes more difficult to manage

734
00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:29.700
than someone with reduced ejection fraction.

735
00:30:29.700 --> 00:30:32.400
If you consider that what is improving or causing

736
00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:35.580
end diastolic distension or end diastolic volume,

737
00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:37.350
it's that preload which comes in.

738
00:30:37.350 --> 00:30:38.610
They don't relax very well

739
00:30:38.610 --> 00:30:41.370
because they've got these big thick left ventricles.

740
00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:44.910
So what is really improving or helping to maintain

741
00:30:44.910 --> 00:30:46.260
their end diastolic volume,

742
00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:47.670
therefore their stroke volume

743
00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:49.680
is the preload that's coming in.

744
00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:52.170
These folks tend to be very volume dependent

745
00:30:52.170 --> 00:30:55.800
and you can over volume, over diurese them in a hurry.

746
00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:57.780
They can go from doing okay,

747
00:30:57.780 --> 00:30:58.830
another hit of Lasix

748
00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:01.350
and all of a sudden they've decompensated.

749
00:31:01.350 --> 00:31:02.760
Same thing with heart rate.

750
00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:04.680
Again, keep in mind that elevated heart rate

751
00:31:04.680 --> 00:31:07.083
may be what is maintaining their cardiac output.

752
00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:09.910
So decreasing heart rate beta blocker,

753
00:31:09.910 --> 00:31:12.420
a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker.

754
00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:13.890
While I said that they're not good drugs

755
00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:17.070
from a heart failure standpoint, it's one of these,

756
00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:19.020
like if you kind of grit your teeth and say,

757
00:31:19.020 --> 00:31:22.473
okay, you may still have a place for diltiazem in this case.

758
00:31:23.760 --> 00:31:26.550
Afib, a flutter can be horrible for these individuals.

759
00:31:26.550 --> 00:31:29.580
'Cause not only do they have the heart rate increase,

760
00:31:29.580 --> 00:31:31.590
decrease in their diastolic filling time,

761
00:31:31.590 --> 00:31:33.210
they lose their atrial kick

762
00:31:33.210 --> 00:31:36.153
and so their end diastolic volume can tank pretty quickly.

763
00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:40.290
Advanced heart failure care ICDs

764
00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:43.380
typically with a EF less than 35%,

765
00:31:43.380 --> 00:31:45.360
class two to class three symptoms.

766
00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:46.920
And even though it sounds like

767
00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:49.290
rationing life expectancy of a year,

768
00:31:49.290 --> 00:31:50.670
resynchronization therapy,

769
00:31:50.670 --> 00:31:52.860
basically those who have a wide QRS,

770
00:31:52.860 --> 00:31:54.180
that's in essence saying

771
00:31:54.180 --> 00:31:56.010
we're going to now resynchronize the ventricles

772
00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:57.960
to contract simultaneously

773
00:31:57.960 --> 00:32:00.060
and that improves cardiac output.

774
00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:02.010
An LVAD or left ventricular assist device

775
00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:04.650
is basically a bridge to a new heart.

776
00:32:04.650 --> 00:32:07.303
And with that, thank you so much for your time.

777
00:32:07.303 --> 00:32:08.615
(audience applauding)

778
00:32:08.615 --> 00:32:11.198
(bright music)

